We borrow PKB's design ideas: the per-rank output-compare evaluation pattern,
the ThunderKittens-2 timing rigor (500 warmup / 100 timed iterations), and the
distributed-op problem space (collectives, sequence-parallel repartition,
expert-parallel all-to-all, quantized communication).

Where any reference implementation in this repo is adapted from a specific PKB
source file, that file carries a header naming the source and stating that it
was modified, per Apache-2.0 section 4(b). Most references here are written
independently and credit PKB as design inspiration only.

What KernelBench-Multi adds on top of PKB: a curated, hand- and subagent-audited
deck; rank-asymmetric correctness gates that defeat rank-symmetry reward hacks;
a busbw-only roofline that grades inter-GPU (NVLink) efficiency rather than
single-GPU compute; and the reward-hack audit pipeline inherited from
KernelBench-Hard (contamination guard, lint tripwire, mandatory manual audit).

